---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Galaxy Bimodality - ArXiv Atlas";
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <div class="page-header">
            <h1>Galaxy Bimodality</h1>
            <div class="page-meta">
                <span class="tag">Structure</span>
                <span class="tag">Evolution</span>
                <span class="tag">Star Formation</span>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="content">
            <h2 id="section-0">Overview</h2>
            <p>
                Galaxy bimodality refers to the observed dichotomy in the galaxy population: galaxies tend to cluster 
                into two distinct groups — <strong>star-forming disk galaxies</strong> (blue, late-type) and 
                <strong>quiescent early-type galaxies</strong> (red, early-type). This bimodal distribution is evident 
                in color-magnitude diagrams, where galaxies separate into a "red sequence" and a "blue cloud."
            </p>

            <h2 id="section-1">Key Observations</h2>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Color-Magnitude Relation:</strong> Galaxies show a bimodal distribution in optical color vs. luminosity space</li>
                <li><strong>Morphological Split:</strong> Late-type spirals vs. early-type ellipticals/lenticulars</li>
                <li><strong>Star Formation:</strong> Active star formation in blue cloud; minimal in red sequence</li>
                <li><strong>Structural Differences:</strong> Disks vs. bulge-dominated, different size-mass relations</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 id="section-2">Physical Mechanisms</h2>
            <p>Multiple processes may drive the bimodality:</p>
            
            <h3>Gas Processes</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Gas exhaustion through star formation</li>
                <li>Gas heating (AGN feedback, stellar feedback)</li>
                <li>Gas stripping in dense environments</li>
            </ul>

            <h3>Gravitational Processes</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>Major mergers transforming disks into ellipticals</li>
                <li>Minor mergers building bulges</li>
                <li>Secular evolution (bar instabilities, etc.)</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 id="section-3">Open Questions</h2>
            <ul>
                <li>What is the relative importance of gas processes vs. gravitational processes?</li>
                <li>How does environment (field vs. cluster) affect the transition?</li>
                <li>What role does AGN feedback play in quenching?</li>
                <li>Is the bimodality a result of one or multiple evolutionary paths?</li>
            </ul>

